Description: CLAUDIUS, A.D. 41-54. AV Aureus (7.72 gms), Lugdunum Mint, ca. A.D. 44-45. NGC Ch F, Strike: 5/5 Surface: 4/5.RIC-25; Cal-361B. Obverse: Laureate head of Claudius right; Reverse: View of Praetorian camp with "IMPER RECEPT" across front; soldier standing guard atop. A beautiful Aureus bearing a full, well-centered strike that yields complete legends and a great representation of the coin's interesting architectural reverse type. Though it shows some marks and wear from circulation, the emperor's portrait remains clear and a handsome reddish tone enhances the golden surfaces.The Praetorian Guard, the Roman emperor's personal bodyguard corps, was at its most powerful during the Julio-Claudian era. Sejanus, the Praetorian commander during the reign of Tiberius, flaunted this power by bending the emperor to his will and enmeshing himself into the ruling family. In A.D. 41, the guardsmen orchestrated both the assassination of emperor Caligula and elevation of his reluctant uncle Claudius to the throne. As emperor of the Roman world, Claudius was keenly aware that he owed his power to the Praetorians and, what's more, that they could easily dispose of him as they had done to his predecessor if they ever found him to be a nuisance. The reverse type seen on this piece explicitly highlights the intimate and precarious relationship between the emperor and his guard. Roman gold coinage was almost exclusively used by the senatorial aristocracy and military elite, so this Aureus was likely a direct message to members of the Praetorian cohort.
Auction Name: NumisBids: Stack's Bowers & Ponterio May 2024 World CCO Auction

Description: FRANCE. Liberation of Paris Bronze Award Medal, 1944. Paris Mint. CHOICE ALMOST UNCIRCULATED.By L. Bazor. Diameter: 68mm; Weight: 159.58 gms. Issued and engraved 1944 to Guy Genermont. Obverse: Plain clothes soldier standing facing, head left, holding up rifle and pistol to head; ravaged cityscape in background, with shell casing, tank, truck, and overturned tractor; Reverse: LIBERATION DE PARIS / JOURNEES / DU 19 AU 26 AOUT, cross of Lorraine on central band between two laurel branches; engraved in three lines below, "AU CHEF AMBULANCIER / GENERMONT GUY / EN SOUVENIR DE CES HEURES." Edge: [cornucopia] BRONZE. Deep brown surfaces, with some light rub upon the high points.VE Day, or Victory in Europe Day, had traditionally been a holiday marking the surrender of Germany to allied forces on 8 May 1945. As such, the 8th of May was a bank holiday in France from 1953 through 1959, at which point it was demoted simply to a commemoration. In 1975, then president Valry Giscard d'Estaing removed the tradition altogether, choosing instead to honor the following day in the calendar, which marked the 25th anniversary of the calling for friendship with Germany and a European Union. Among those who had served in World War II, and especially during the liberation of Paris, this backpedaling away from a holiday or even mere recognition was a step too far. In 1980, Guy Generment (the recipient of this medal and president of an association for decorated servicepeople), announced to the French cabinet that "...the decorated veterans saw around 400,000 of their comrades killed and awarded medals posthumously, and they don't think that dedicating one day a year to them is over the top." Following the election of Franois Mitterrand as president, the original holiday was brought back the next year in 1981.
Auction Name: NumisBids: Stack's Bowers & Ponterio May 2024 World CCO Auction

Description: GERMANY. Prussia. Franz Joseph Gall Silver Medal, 1805. PCGS SPECIMEN-58.Sommer-A-124; Brettauer-374. By F. Loos & A. Hoffmann. Obverse: Bust right; Reverse: Draped skull right set upon altar decorated with torch and serpent-entwined staff crossed in saltire. Deeply toned, with some light hairlines below.Gall was a noted physiologist and neuroanatomist, and most well-known as the father of phrenology. From an early age, Gall was interested in the classification and differences in human abilities and tendencies. He began noting that these aptitudes could be linked to various areas of the brain, each responsible for different characteristics. The random bumps on one's skull were, he believed, due to pressure exerted by the brain from beneath. Wildly popular and accepted in his time, phrenology is now viewed entirely as a pseudoscience that has been repeatedly disproven. Nevertheless, the contributions which he made to modern neuroscience cannot be overlooked. PCGS SPECIMEN-58.
Auction Name: NumisBids: Stack's Bowers & Ponterio May 2024 World CCO Auction

Commemorating the life and accomplishments of the German statesman. Description: GERMANY. Weimar Republic. Gustav Stresemann Bronze Medal, 1929. Munich Mint. GEM UNCIRCULATED.K-432. By K. Goetz. Diameter: 36mm; Weight: 19.83 gms. Commemorating the life and accomplishments of the German statesman. Obverse: Bust right; Reverse: Four tombstones, bearing his great accomplishments, under a weeping willow: LO CARNO 1925, THOIRY, GENF 1926, HAAG 1929. Edge: BAYER. HAUPTMNZAMT. Olive-brown surfaces, with a great glossy nature.A departure from Goetz's usual satirical issues, this example instead commemorates the life and achievements of Stresemann, an important figure in the interwar period of Germany. In his role as Minister of Foreign Affairs (from 1923 until his death in 1929), he negotiated several treaties which saw greater normalization of Germany following World War I. Starting in 1923 with Locarno, post-war borders were agreed upon, with a rapprochement between France and Germany (mainly in the form of German bond-backing of the Franc and a French withdrawal from the Rhineland) occurring a few years later at Thoiry. Soon thereafter, he saw Germany's admittance into the League of Nations at Geneva, and then an ultimate withdrawal from the Ruhr while at the Hague in 1929. Sadly, Stresemann would never see this final act, as he passed away before it took effect in 1930, though he would also thankfully not see Germany's aggressive rise again just a few short years with the emergence of Hitler. A haunting and provocative issue from the typically cheeky Goetz.
Auction Name: NumisBids: Stack's Bowers & Ponterio May 2024 World CCO Auction

Description: GREAT BRITAIN. Royal Horticultural Society Silver Award Medal, 1957. London Mint. UNCIRCULATED.BHM-Unlisted; Eimer-Unlisted. Originally by W. Wyon. Diameter: 55mm; Weight: 71.86 gms. Engraved and awarded to Knud Stormly Hansen. Obverse: Female allegory of Horticulture standing facing, head lowered slightly right, holding bouquet of flowers and wreath; around in background, four muses in circular pattern and holding open wreaths; Reverse: Floral wreath with many components containing legend THE ROYAL HORTICULTURAL SOCIETY and engraving in five lines "TO / K. STORMLY HANSEN / FOR AN EXHIBIT OF / CARNATIONS / 5 NOV. 1957." Edge: A few light marks, otherwise plain. Highly prooflike, with some argent frosting upon the devices and a great deal of mirrored brilliance in the fields; some lightly scattered hairlines are noted for completeness.Knud Stormly Hansen was a commercial gardener who began with growing vegetables in the years leading up to World War II, switching to the much more profitable tobacco during the war years. Afterward, he returned to the more mundane crops, such as onions, mushrooms, and strawberries. By the 1950's, nearly all carnations were being attacked by disease, and Hansen, along with Professor Ernst Hellmers, developed a method whereby mother plants could be tested for disease. Knud clearly had a great role in the world of carnations, as nearly 16 years after receiving this medal, he is mentioned as having grown "...his first pixie (Elegance) in the summer of 1960 near Copenhagen. None of the Danish florists would buy them so he gave a van load of flowers to the major department store in Copenhagen as a promotion venture to popularize spray carnations. Stormly continued these promotions in Copenhagen and Stockholm for several years and no doubt helped start the popularity of this new crop. Lennard Hakansson has taken up where Stormly left off and today miniatures make up at least 35 percent of carnations grown in the Scandinavian countries. Their popularity is on the increase in most of Europe." ("Breeding Pixie Carnations," by W. D. Holley in "Colorado Flower Growers Association, Inc.," Bulletin 278, July 1973.). .

Description: RUSSIA. Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty Silver Medal, 1988. Leningrad (St. Petersburg) Mint. PCGS PROOF-69 Deep Cameo.KMX-MB2; Shkurko & Salykov-1819. Mintage: 1,000. Obverse: -            USA AND USSR INF TREATY, faade of the U.S. Capitol and the Kremlin; Reverse: FOR PEACE AND COOPERATION -    , clasped hands over representations of the flags of the United States and Soviet Union. Edge: Reeded. Argent, highly frosted devices and richly mirrored fields, with a deep cameo nature; an exceptionally flawless specimen. Tied with just one other as the only representatives of the type in the PCGS census.As the Cold War between the United States/NATO and the Soviet Union/Warsaw Pact continued to escalate in the 1980's, the increasing likelihood of "mutually assured destruction," on account of growing stockpiles of nuclear weaponry, was seemingly front of mind to all parties involved. As such, cooler heads began to prevail, and a treaty between the two superpowers was reached late in 1987, culminating in a signing between Ronald Reagan and Mikhail Gorbachev in Washington, D.C. Though this treaty served well to cool relations and de-escalate tensions, it has since expired, with relations between the two signatories having obviously disintegrated to quite possibly their lowest levels ever. One wonders when, or even if, such a handshake, as depicted here, will ever again occur between the two superpowers. PCGS PROOF-69 Deep Cameo.

Description:
THE KIAN COLLECTION - PART 2.  SAFAVID DYNASTY.  Esma'il I. 907-930 AH (1501-1524).  Early Shahi 916 AH (1510), Harat Mint. 9.64 g. Album 2576. Farahbakhsh 7. cf. Rabino 77 (2 Shahi 921 AH). Selten / Rare. berdurchschnittlich gut ausgeprgt / Extraordinarily well struck. Leicht gereinigt / Lightly cleaned. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.
(~ 365/USD 400)

The Safavid Dynasty, ruling from 1501 to 1736 CE, was a pivotal period in Persian history. Founded by Shah Esma_'il I., it marked the resurgence of Persian sovereignty after centuries of foreign domination. The Safavids established Twelver Shia Islam as the state religion, leading to a distinct cultural identity that blended Persian and Shia traditions. Under Shah Abbas I, the empire reached its zenith, with flourishing art, architecture, and trade. However, internal strife and external pressures, particularly from the Ottoman Empire and later Tsarist Russia, weakened the Safavids, leading to their eventual collapse in the 18th century. Despite their downfall, the Safavid legacy endures through their contributions to Persian culture, art, and religious identity.
Esma'il I. (1487-1524), son of Seikh Heidar, enthronement 1501 in Tabriz. He died on May 23, 1524.

Purchased from A. Shams, Frankfurt, in 1985.
Auction Name: NumisBids: SINCONA AG Auction 88

Mahmud Hotaki, also known as Ghilzai, son of Mir Vais Khan, a Pashtun ruler of the Hotak Dynasty, was born in 1697. Mahmud launched an expedition against Soltan Hosayn in 1722, and after defeating Hosayn's forces in the Battle of Golnabad, he encircled Isfahan and blocked all the roads leading to the city. The siege lasted from March to October 1722 and ended by the abdiction of Soltan Hosayn.

Mahmud was then enthroned on October 23, 1722, as the new Shah of Persia. He was killed by Ashraf Khan on April 22, 1725, at the age of 28.

Ahmad Durrani, son of Mohammad Zaman Khan Abdali, was born in 1722. He is the founder of the Durrani Dynasty. Ahmad was the commander of the Abdali Regiment in Nader Shah's army. In 1751 he captured Neishapour and Mashhad which were ruled by Nader's grandson Shahrokh, who was eventually pardoned by the new ruler. Ahmad Durrani died on October 16, 1772, in Maruf, Qandahar.
The Durrani Dynasty, established by Ahmad Shah Durrani in 1747, played a crucial role in the shaping of Afghanistan as a unified nation-state. Ahmad Shah, also known as Ahmad Shah Durrani or Ahmad Shah Abdali, rose to power after leading a successful Afghan tribal confederation against Persian and Indian forces. He founded the Durrani Empire, with its capital in Kandahar, which encompassed parts of present-day Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Iran.

Under Ahmad Shah and his successors, particularly his son Taimur Shah and grandson Zaman Shah, the Durrani Dynasty maintained a degree of stability and centralization, albeit with occasional internal conflicts and external pressures from neighbouring powers. The dynasty's rule saw the establishment of diplomatic relations with various European powers, notably the British and the Russians, as well as efforts to modernize the administration and military.

However, the Durrani Dynasty faced significant challenges, including tribal rivalries, foreign invasions, and internal strife over succession. By the early 19th century, the empire began to weaken, and Afghanistan fell into a period of fragmentation and instability after Ahmad Shah's death in 1772. Despite its eventual decline and dissolution in 1856, the Durrani Dynasty contributed to the nation's identity and shaped its political landscape for centuries to come.

Nader Shah (1688-1747), son of Emam Qoli, was enthroned on March 8, 1736. He was assassinated in 1747 by his own commanders
The Afsharid Dynasty, which emerged in 1736, was founded by Nader Shah Afshar. His military prowess allowed him to carve out a vast empire that stretched from the Caucasus to Central Asia and from the Indian subcontinent to the Persian Gulf.

Under Nader Shah's rule, the Afsharid Dynasty experienced a brief but remarkable period of territorial expansion and centralized administration. Nader Shah's military campaigns brought immense wealth and cultural treasures to Persia, including the famed Peacock Throne and the Koh-i-Noor diamond.

However, the empire's rapid expansion also brought significant challenges, including internal dissent, external pressures from neighbouring powers, and revolts in distant territories. Nader Shah's assassination in 1747 marked the beginning of the dynasty's decline, as his successors struggled to maintain control over the vast territories he had conquered.

The Afsharid Dynasty's rule came to an end in 1796 with the rise of local rulers and the emergence of new Persian dynasties, notably the Zand Dynasty and later the Qajar Dynasty. Despite its relatively short duration, the Afsharid Dynasty left a lasting legacy in Persian history, particularly through its military achievements, cultural advancements, and the centralization of power during Nader Shah's reign.
While this coin formerly was assigned to Tahmasp II, according to the current state of knowledge this coin is to be assigned to Nader Shah as viceroy.

Shahrokh (1734-1796), son of Reza Qoli and grandson of Nader Shah, was born on March 21, 1734. He had several enthronements, first as king of Herat in 1747, and then on September 30, 1748, he was crowned as Shah of Persia. Shahrokh was enthroned for a third time in the first quarter of 1750. Later when he lost his authority, Shahrokh regained power under the protection of Ahmad Shah Durrani on May 8, 1755. He died in May 1796.

NGC AU58.(~ 625/USD 680)Wrong date AH 1171 (1758) on NGC label.The Zand Dynasty, which emerged in 1751, was founded by Karim Khan Zand, a military commander who rose to power in southern Persia following the collapse of the Afsharid Dynasty. Karim Khan established his capital in Shiraz and ruled over a relatively stable and prosperous kingdom.Under Karim Khan's leadership, the Zand Dynasty implemented administrative reforms, promoted trade and agriculture, and fostered a period of cultural revival. Karim Khan himself was known for his relatively benevolent rule and patronage of the arts, literature, and architecture.However, upon Karim Khan's death in 1779, the Zand Dynasty faced internal power struggles and external threats from rival factions and neighbouring powers, notably the Qajar Dynasty and the resurgent Afsharids. These challenges eventually led to the downfall of the Zand Dynasty, as it was overthrown by Agha Mohammad Khan Qajar, founder of the Qajar Dynasty, in 1794.Karim Khan (1705-1779), son of Inaq Khan, was born in 1705. He was the founder of the Zand Dynasty, ruling from 1751 to 1779. He ruled all of Persia except for Khorasan. He died on March 1, 1779.Purchased from Sotheby's, London, in 1982.

(~ 210/USD 225)

The Qajar Dynasty, which ruled Persia from 1794 to 1925, was founded by Agha Mohammad Khan Qajar, who rose to power by overthrowing the Zand Dynasty. The Qajars established their capital in Tehran and faced numerous challenges, including internal unrest, foreign invasions, and struggles for modernization.

Despite efforts at centralization and reform, the Qajar Dynasty's rule was marked by political instability, economic decline, and territorial losses to expanding European powers. However, the dynasty also witnessed significant cultural developments, with Persian literature, art, and architecture flourishing during this period.

The Qajar era saw Persia caught up in the middle of geopolitical rivalries between Tsarist Russia and the British Empire, which sought to exploit Persia's strategic location and resources. This led to several conflicts and treaties that further weakened the Qajar monarchy.

The dynasty's decline accelerated in the 19th century, culminating in the Persian Constitutional Revolution of 19051911, which led to the establishment of Iran's first constitution and parliament. The Qajar Dynasty officially came to an end in 1925 with the overthrow of Ahmad Shah Qajar and the establishment of the Pahlavi Dynasty under Reza Shah Pahlavi.
Mohammad Hasan Khan (1715-1759), son of Fath Ali Khan, was born in 1715 in Astarabad. He was chief of the Qoyunlu tribe in Mazandaran and declared himself independent in 1750. In 1759, Mohammad was overthrown by Karim Khan Zand. He was killed on February 12, 1759, in a battle with Zand forces.

Abbas Mirza (1789-1833), son of Fath-'Ali Shah, was born on August 26, 1789, in Nava, Mazandaran. He became Governor of Azarbaijan in 1798 at the age of 10. Abbas Mirza developed a reputation as a military commander during the Russo-Persian and Ottoman-Persian wars between 1804 and 1828. He died on October 25, 1833, in Mashhad.
Prince Abbas Mirza (1789-1833) was the second son of Fath-'Ali Shah Qajar and chosen to follow his father on the throne of Persia. Due to the fact that he died one year before his father in 1833, his eldest son Mohammad Shah Qajar succeeded Fath-'Ali Shah Qajar to the throne.
Purchased from M. Afshar, Geneva, in 2015.

Hosayn Ali Mirza Farmanfarma (1790-1835), son of Fath-'Ali Shah, was born on August 12, 1790, in Amol. Being the Governor of Fars, he proclaimed himself king Hosayn Ali Shah in October 1834, when the news reached him that his father, Fath-'Ali Shah, died on his way to Fars to collect tax arrears from him, despite the fact that his brother Mohammad Mirza was crowned king as Mohammad Shah. After two months, he was defeated by his brother in a battle near Tehran. He was then imprisoned and blinded on the order of Mohammad Shah, and he died on January 16, 1835, of cholera.

One of the most important Greek cities in Lower Italy, founded by the Achaeans, the pre-Dorian population of Thessaly and the Peloponnese, with the participation of Sybaris on the shallow shore of the Gulf of Taranto between the deltas of the Bradano and Basento rivers around 700 BC.

Two founding heroes are named: Metabos and Leukippos. Little is known about the history of Metapont. Shortly before 500 BC, Pythagoras came to Metapont from Kroton with his school; he died here and was then honoured as a hero. In 415 Metapont supports Athens in the Sicilian expedition. Captured several times during the 2nd Punic War, Metapont was destroyed by Rome in 207. Cicero only knew it as a ruined city. The extensive coinage gives us a better idea of the importance of the city than the sources. It begins with large issues of incuse nomoi with the completed image of an ear of corn. The ear of corn, the emblem of Demeter, remains the emblem of Metapont. In the Classical and early Hellenistic periods, a large repertoire of images of gods was added to the coinage like hardly any other mint in Greece; some are named with the inscription, e.g. Acheloos, Homonoia, Hygieia. Die cutters from Herakleia and Taranto signed in the 4th century: Aristoxenos, Kal... Bronze coinage also began during this period, with some coins bearing the rare denomination "obolos". Metapont has been the subject of archaeological research for decades; a number of sanctuaries (Apollon Lykeios, Hera, Zeus Aglaios) have been excavated. Two rows of peristasis columns ("Tavole Palatine") from the temple of Hera are still standing. The excavations have revealed that a workshop of Italic red-figure vase painting was active in Metapont.

Description: THE GARRULUS COLLECTION. LUCANIA. Poseidonia (Paestum). Nomos c. 540-510 BC. (7.51 g, 12 h) POS retrograde, Poseidon walking right, wielding trident, chlamys draped over both arms. Rv. POS raised and retrograde, as obverse but incuse, no serpent. Gorini 31, 3 ans 214-215 (same dies) and Antiken Museum Basel 158. Selten / Rare. Herrlicher sptarchaischer Stil. Alte Sammlungspatina / Wonderful late archaic style. Old collection's patina. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.(~ 15'625/USD 17'045)The three Doric temples of Paestum in the Lucanian lowland near the sea are among the architectural monuments of the Greek world. The city that built these temples was not called Paestum, but Poseidonia. It was founded from Sybaris in the early 7th century BC 8 kilometres south of the delta of the Sele. The main god was Poseidon. Temples and coins testify to a great flourishing in the 6th and 5th centuries; an important ceramic workshop was active in the 4th century, at a time when Poseidonia was no longer occupied by Greeks but by Lucanians and had taken the name Paiston = Paestum. Paestum became a Latin colony in 273 BC. Incuse nomoi have been struck here since around 530 BC - as in Metapont, Sybaris, Kaulonia and Kroton - but differ from the coinage of these four cities in their lighter weight and greater variation in the coin design. After a longer break, the incuse coinage is replaced by double-sided nomoi, which show Poseidon in an archaic position on the obverse and the bull on the reverse, whose image is derived from the founding city of Sybaris.From auction Mnzen und Medaillen AG 90, Basel, June 2000, lot 206. Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  LUCANIA.  Thurium.  Stater c. 400-385 BC. (7.36 g, 6 h) Signed by E.... . Head of Athena to right, wearing necklace and crested Attic helmet adorned with a figure of Skylla (she is human to the hips, but has the tail of a sea serpent and foreparts of two dogs at her waist); to right, here off flan. Rv. Bull charging to right, with lashing tail and head lowered; in exergue, river fish swimming to right. Gulbenkian 88. SNG Lloyd 476. SNG Oxford 930. SNG Lockett 482 (this coin). Selten / Rare. Kleine Kratzer und Felder etwas geglttet / Some scratches and fields smoothed. Fast vorzglich / About extremely fine.
(~ 1'565/USD 1'705)

Herakleia and Thurioi were the last cities to be founded in western Greece. The main group of the founders were the expelled Sybarites who, after 60 years, settled a new city in their old homeland in 443 BC; they were helped by the Athens of Pericles. Athena in the Attic helmet and the bull of Sybaris are stamped on the coins of the new city. A friend of Pericles, Lampon, led the founding procession. Herodotus, who died in Thurioi, and the philosopher Protagoras, who drafted the constitution, were also involved. Lysias, the orator, and Empedocles, the philosopher, were active in Thurioi for a time. During the Sicilian expedition of Athens in 415-413 BC, Thurioi remained loyal to its mother city, but then turned to Sparta. In the 4th century BC, Thurioi had to defend itself against the Brettians, Lucanians and Tarentum with varying success. Occupied by Rome in 282 BC, conquered by Carthage in the 2nd Punic War, Thurioi became a Roman colony called Copia in 194 BC.

Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  BRUTTIUM.  Kroton.  Stater c. 380 BC. (8.05 g, 5 h) Eagle, with closed wings and head turned back, standing to left on stag's head. Rv. Tripod with three ring handles and legs ending in lion's paws; to left, ivy leaf. De Hirsch 223. Gulbenkian 127. Kraay/Hirmer 269 (this coin). SNG ANS 351-352. SNG Oxford 1511. Sehr selten / Very rare. Prachtvolle Erhaltung / Magnificent condition. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.
(~ 6'770/USD 7'385)

Kroton was at times the most powerful Greek city in Lower Italy. Around 720 BC, Achaer founded it at the river delta of the Aisaros (now Esaro) into the Ionian Sea, halfway between Metapont and Lokroi. The philosopher Pythagoras, expelled from Samos, founded a brotherhood with strict rules here around 530 BC, which controlled the fortunes of the city for decades. However, Pythagoras had to flee from Kroton and died in Metapont. The destruction of Sybaris by Croton and the minting of the splendid incuse nomoi with the tripod occurred during this period of greatest splendour. Milon of Kroton was the most famous athlete of his time. We know little about the history of the city in the 5th century, and there seems to have been a longer break in the minting of coins. Around 390 BC, Kroton founded a league of Greek cities against the Lucanians and Syracuse, but was conquered by Dionysius I in 388 BC, liberated again after twelve years of occupation, reoccupied by Agathocles in 299 BC, and finally subjugated by Rome in 277 BC, which made Kroton a colony in 194 BC. The main cults were Hera Lakinia - a pillar of her temple still stands (at Capo Colonna 10 km south-east, the eastern tip of the Lucanian-British peninsula) -, Zeus, Apollo and Heracles, whose images and emblems appear on the coins; Heracles as the founder of the city (inscription OIKIETAE), Apollo in battle against the python snake. Croton's power in archaic times manifests itself on the so-called alliance coins. Only small traces of the ancient city have been preserved in today's Crotone

Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  SICILY.  Akragas.  Tetradrachm c. 460 BC. (17.49 g, 4 h) AKPAC - ANTOS  Eagle standing left, with closed wings. Rv. Crab, shell resembling human face. Westermark 349.4 (this coin). SNG ANS 973 and Gulbenkian 161 (same dies). Hirmer 171 (same reverse die). berdurchschnittlich gut ausgeprgt / Extraordinarily well struck. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.
(~ 5'210/USD 5'680)

Akragas, today Agrigento, the second largest city in Greek Sicily after Syracuse, was founded by Gela, the Rhodian settlement, around 600 BC. The inhabitants were Dorians. The city reached its greatest prosperity in the 5th century BC. The tyrant Theron and Gelon of Syracuse defeated the Carthaginians at Himera in 480. At that time, Akragas built its temples on the rocky terrace between the castle hill and the sea, many of which are still preserved today. The largest, dedicated to Zeus Olympios, remained unfinished. Akragas was destroyed by Carthage in 406/5 BC and never regained its former importance in later times. The minting of coins began in the second half of the 6th century BC. A simple symbolism (eagle of Zeus/crab) characterised the coin designs until the High Classical period. Around 430 BC, these were "activated" as in most Greek mints in Sicily: The eagles become a pair eating their prey, a galloping quadruped appears on the obverse, and all kinds of accessories (fish, shells, urchins) are added. The coins of this last period are among the most important masterpieces of classical Greek coinage.

Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  SICILY.  Leontinoi.  Tetradrachm 450/440 BC. (17.24 g, 7 h) Laureate head of Apollo to left. Rv. L-EO-NTIN-O-N Head of roaring lion to left; around, four barley grains. Rizzo Tf. 23,19 (same dies). SNG ANS 236 (same dies). Prgung auf breitem Schrtling / Struck on broad flan. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.
(~ 2'605/USD 2'840)

Halfway between Katane and Syracuse, on a hill south of Symaithos, Naxos founded Leontinoi around 729 BC, after the Sikelian residents had been expelled. As in Katane, the other Naxian colony, Apollo, whose Delphic oracle had led the settlers here, was the main god. At the beginning of the 5th century BC, Hippocrates of Gela conquered the city and installed Ainesidemos as tyrant. From then on, the fate of the city depended on the stronger poleis in the neighbourhood. Hieron settled the exiled Naxians and Catanaeans here. After the fall of the tyrants in 466 BC, Leontinoi turned back to the Ionian tribesmen; it concluded a treaty of friendship with Athens in 433 BC, which led to several Athenian interventions.

Gorgias of Leontinoi, the famous sophist, led an envoy to Athens. In 422 BC, Syracuse occupied the city and partially destroyed it. Leontinoi has never recovered since. Today, Lentini is the centre of Sicilian orange production. Coinage was initially influenced by Syracuse and Gela in the first quarter of the 5th century BC. Rich silver issues testify to the importance of the city; the Apollo heads (from around 450 BC) compete with those of the neighbouring city of Katane, but were cut by other die cutters.

Description: THE GARRULUS COLLECTION. SICILY. Panormos. Tetradrachm c. 340 BC. (16.87 g, 6 h) Quadriga galloping to left; above, Nike flying right to crown the charioteer who bends forward, holding kentron in his right hand and the reins in his left; in exergue, Punic inscription SYS; above the head of the farthest horse, star. Rv. Head of Kore-Persephone to left, wearing necklace, triple-pendant earring and corn wreath; below chin, swastika; around four dolphins. Jenkins pl. 21, 70 (same dies). Rizzo pl. 66, 1 and SNG Lockett (same dies). Sehr selten / Very rare. Von herrlichem Stil / Of lovely, purely Greek style. Unter der Bste etwas gereinigt / Slightly polished below the bust. Einige kleine Korrosionsstellen, sonst fast prgefrisch / Minor traces of corrosion, otherwise, virtually as struck.(~ 31'250/USD 34'090)There were three major Phoenician cities in western Sicily: Motya, Solunt and Panormos (today's Palermo). From the 6th century BC, Panormos was an important base for Carthage's merchant ships and military operations, but it was not until the 4th century BC that Panormos gained its great importance. Often captured by the Greeks and Romans, but repeatedly recaptured by Carthage, Panormos fell to the Romans in 254 BC. Coinage began in the later 5th century BC following the Syracusan model. In the 4th century, Panormos was one of the major "Siculo-Punic" mints. The Punic inscription "SYS" probably refers to the Semitic name of the city.From auction Leu 76, Zurich, October 1999, lot 45.From auction Monnaies et Mdailles SA 32, Basel, October 1966, lot 68.This wonderful coin was inspired by the Syracusan Arethusa heads of Euainetos and is the most beautiful of all the Siculo-Punic tetradrachms of Panormos. It was surely engraved by a Greek artist, possibly by a disciple of Euainetos himself. The swastika, which in the entire Siculo-Punic coinage only occurs on this reverse die, is a puzzle. Jenkins provides no explanation for its appearance, though it is, of course, a well-known solar symbol. Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  SICILY.  Syracuse.  Tetradrachm c. 485-480 BC. (17.33 g, 8 h) Slow quadriga left, the driver, wearing sleeveless, long chiton, holding the reins with both his hands; above, Nike flying left to crown horses. Rv. SVR-AK-OSI-ON Head of Arethusa right, wearing a necklace, the long hair tied up in the neck into a pearl band; around, four dolphins, all within incuse round. Boehringer cf. 126, 73 (R 48, same die) and 128, 80 (V 37, same die). Feiner Stil und aussergewhnlich erhalten / Nice style and extraordinary condition. Vorzglich / Extremely fine.
(~ 7'815/USD 8'525)

Its location with its large natural harbour, open to Greece, predestined Syracuse to become the leading power in Sicily. Founded by Corinth, with one of the first westward colonisation campaigns (directly following Naxos) around 730 BC, Syracuse retained its Doric tribal character and Doric language until Roman times and maintained close contact with the motherland. The urban centre was located on the small island of Ortygia, where the spring of Arethusa emerged; other territories on the mainland were soon acquired.

We know little about its early history, but Syracuse does not appear to have achieved greater importance until the 6th century BC. The minting of coins did not begin until around 520-510 BC, but then immediately with a large issue of tetradrachms and didrachms in Attic standard currency.

Description:
THE GARRULUS COLLECTION.  MACEDONIA.  Akanthos.  Tetradrachm c. 500 BC. (17.02 g, 1 h) Lion to left, attacking bull kneeling to right, head lifted; in exergue, flower. Rv. Quadripartite incuse square. Desneux 3. SNG Delepierre 864. Fast vorzglich / About extremely fine.
(~ 2'605/USD 2'840)

According to the ancient historian Nikolaos of Damaskos, Akanthos was presumably founded by colonists from the island of Andros in 655 BC. The first reliable evidence of the existence of an autonomous polis are the tetradrachms minted from 520 BC. These silver coins were not only used on the Chalcidian peninsula, but also in Sicily, Egypt and Persia. The export of silver in the form of these coins was an important source of income for Akanthos in archaic times, alongside the dominant agriculture.

During the Persian Wars, Akanthos served the Persian general Mardonios in 492 BC and the Persian king Xerxes I in
480 BC as a base for their military operations in the Aegean region. After the defeat of the Persian Empire in 480/79 BC against the alliance of free Greek cities, Akanthos joined the Attic League under the leadership of Athens. Even after the outbreak of the Peloponnesian War between the Greek hegemonic powers Athens and Sparta, the city remained in the Attic League, although most of the poleis of the Chalcidian peninsula fell away from Athens. It was only when the city was threatened by the troops of the Spartan commander Brasidas in 424 BC that Akanthos changed sides. The Nicias Peace of 421 BC between Athens and Sparta provided for the autonomy of the polis, but Acanthus was obliged to pay tribute to Athens. Acanthos probably only gained complete autonomy after 405 BC with the defeat of Athens at Aigospotamoi in the renewed war against Sparta.

In the following decades, its autonomy remained untouched. It finally lost its freedom with the expansion of Macedonia under King Philip II. In the middle of the 4th century BC. News about Akanthos only dates back to 199 BC. In this year, the city was plundered by Roman troops during the Second Macedonian War, but continued to exist until the Roman imperial period.

Description: THE GARRULUS COLLECTION. ATTICA. Athens. Tetradrachm c. 475-465 BC. (17.17 g, 4 h) Head of Athena right, wearing earring, necklace with pendants, and crested Attic helmet decorated with three olive leaves over visor and a spiral palmette on the bowl. Rv. Owl standing right, head facing, spread tail feathers; olive sprig and crescent to left, AQE to right; all within incuse square. 17.17 g. Starr, Athenian Coinage 480-449, (Oxford 1970), 135/136. Starr, New Specimens of Athenian Coinage, 480-449 BC, NC 142, 1982, Taf. 36, 15. Svoronos-Pick Taf. 9, 7. Prachtexemplar / Cabinet piece. Gutes vorzglich / Good extremely fine.(~ 3'125/USD 3'410)Athens was the major urban centre of the polis of the same name, located in Attica. In the Peloponnesian War Athens was leading the Delian League against Sparta and the Peloponnesian League. Athenian democracy was established in 508 BC under Cleisthenes following the tyranny of Isagoras. This system remained remarkably stable, and with a few brief interruptions remained in place for 180 years, until 322 BC. In this period the city a centre for the arts, learning and philosophy, home of Plato's Academy and Aristotle's Lyceum, birthplace of Socrates, Plato, Pericles, Aristophanes, Sophocles, and many other prominent philosophers, writers and politicians of the ancient world. The silver mines of Laurion contributed significantly to the development of Athens in the 5th century BC, when the Athenians learned to prospect, treat, and refine the ore and used the proceeds to build a massive fleet, at the instigation of Themistocles.From auction Leu 72, Zurich, May 1998, lot 208. Description: THE GARRULUS COLLECTION. CORINTH. Stater c. 375-300 BC. (8.66 g, 4 h) Pegasos flying to left; below, Koppa. Rv. Head of Athena to left, wearing Corinthian helmet; to right, E and rose. Ravel 997. BMC 327, pl. 6, 5 (same reverse die). Herrlicher spter klassischer Stil / Wonderful late Classical style. FDC / Uncirculated.(~ 1'565/USD 1'705)From auction Leu 77, Zurich, May 2000, lot 217.Historical references begin with the early 8th century BC, when Corinth began to develop as a commercial center. Between the 8th and 7th centuries, the Bacchiad family ruled Corinth. Cypselus overthrew the Bacchiad family, and between 657 and 550 BC, he and his son Periander ruled Corinth as the Tyrants.In about 550 BC, an oligarchical government seized power. This government allied with Sparta within the Peloponnesian League, and Corinth participated in the Persian Wars and Peloponnesian War as an ally of Sparta. After Sparta's victory, the two allies fell out with one another, and Corinth pursued an independent polis in the various wars of the early 4th century BC. After the Macedonian unification of Greece, the Acrocorinth was the seat of a Macedonian garrison until 243 BC, when the city joined the Achaean League. Nach dem am 8. Oktober 1619 mit dem neugewhlten Kaiser Ferdinand II. geschlossenen Mnchner Vertrag liess Maximilian die Produktion minderhaltiger Silbermnzen noch im selben Monat beginnen. Zunchst wurden die Sechsbtzner (24 Kreuzer-Stcke ohne Nominalbezeichnung) und Grochen (3 Kreuzer) geprgt, ohne Jahreszahl und mit einer Unterwertigkeit von 40%. Dabei hat man sich, in leicht modifizierter Weise, am Mnzfuss des Kriegsgegners also der Aufstndischen in Bhmen orientiert.

Der heilige Laurentius war ein rmischer Diakon zur Zeit von Papst Sixtus II. Nachdem der rmische Kaiser Valerian Sixtus II. im Jahre 258 hatte enthaupten lassen, wurde Laurentius aufgefordert, den christlichen Kirchenschatz innerhalb von drei Tagen herauszugeben. Darauf verteilte Laurentius diesen an die Gemeindemitglieder, versammelte eine Schar von Armen und Kranken, Verkrppelten, Blinden, Leprsen, Witwen und Waisen und prsentierte sie als "den wahren Schatz der Kirche". Diesen Affront nahm man ihm dermassen bel, dass er, mehrfach gefoltert, auf einem glhenden Eisenrost hingerichtet wurde. Aus diesem Grund wird der Mrtyrer mit dem Rost als Attribut dargestellt. Obwohl die Reichsstadt Nrnberg sehr frh zum Protestantismus bergetreten war, schmlerte dies die Verehrung der beiden Schutzheiligen der Stadt nicht. Nach St. Laurentius und St. Sebald sind die beiden Hauptkirchen der Stadt benannt und beide Heilige finden sich auf vielen Mnzen der Stadt wieder.

Description:
DEUTSCHLAND.  Aachen, Reichsmnzsttte.  Ludwig der Fromme, 814-840.  Solidus (814-819). Imperiale Reprsentationsprgung aus einer unbekannten Mnzsttte (vielleicht Aachen). +DN HLVDOVVICVS IMP AVC Brustbild nach rechts mit Lorbeerkranz. Rv. +MVNVS DIVINVM Kreuz in Lorbeerkranz. 4.29 g. Depeyrot 8. M./G. 515. Von grsster Seltenheit / Of the highest rarity. Sehr schn / Very fine.
(~ 18'750/USD 20'455)

Die wenigen goldenen Solidi gehren sicherlich zu den spektakulrsten Prgungen aus der Regierungszeit Ludwigs des Frommen (814-840). Sie sind Ausdruck des Machtanspruchs des noch relativ jungen karolingischen Kaisertums und drcken seine Gleichrangigkeit mit Byzanz in Nominal, Gewicht und Mnzbild aus.

Die Legende MVNVS DIVINVM ("Gttliches Geschenk") ist oftmals als Hinweis auf die unerwartete Regierung Ludwigs des Frommen gedeutet worden, dessen eigentlich fr die Nachfolge bestimmten Brder Pippin und Karl bereits vor ihm verstarben. Am 11. September 813 setzte er sich auf Befehl seines Vaters, Karls des Grossen (768-814), in der Aachener Pfalzkapelle selbst die Krone auf. Damit wurde zum ersten Mal das Kaisertum von einem Vater ohne Einflussnahme des Papstes noch zu Lebzeiten an den Sohn weitergeben.

Eine andere Erklrung ist, dass sich die Umschrift auf Kreuz und Kranz der Rckseite als Symbol der gttlichen und weltlichen Macht bezieht. Die Krone (das lat. Wort corona bedeutet sowohl "Krone" als auch "Kranz") wre demnach als gttliches Geschenk an den Herrscher aufzufassen.

Die Prgung dieser Stcke fand vermutlich anlsslich der erneuten Krnung und Salbung am 5. Oktober 816 in Reims durch Papst Stephan IV. (816-817) statt und hat somit zeremoniellen Charakter. Alle bekannten Exemplare lassen sich auf vier Stempelpaare zurckfhren, was fr eine in ihrem Umfang begrenzte Emission spricht.

Als Prgeort nahm W. Hvernick Dorestad an, was fr die spteren Exemplare und Nachahmungen von grberem Stempelschnitt mglich sein mag. Der ausgesprochen "imperiale Charakter" dieser Prgung und das eindrucksvolle Portrt machen jedoch eine Prgung an einem Zentralort karolingischer Herrschaft - namentlich Aachen - wahrscheinlicher. Selbst wenn die Stcke nicht fr den allgemeinen Geldverkehr gedacht waren, so sind sie dennoch als Zahlungsmittel benutzt worden, wie friesische Nachahmungen nahelegen. Es gab also wohl auch noch in der ersten Hlfte des 9. Jahrhunderts ein gewisses Bedrfnis nach Goldgeld. In jedem Fall sind es bis zu den Augustalen Kaiser Friedrichs II. (1215-1250) die letzten Goldmnzen eines abendlndischen Kaisers.

Literaturangaben:
- Coupland, S.: Money and Coinage under Louis the Pious, in: Francia 17/1, Sigmaringen 1990, S. 27.

- Hvernick, W.: Die Anfnge der karolingischen Goldprgung in Nordwesteuropa, in: HBN 6-7 (1952-1953), S. 55-60. - Kluge, B.: Numismatik des Mittelalters. Handbuch und Thesaurus Nummorum Medii Aevi, Berlin / Wien 2007, S.89. - Grierson, P. / Blackburn, M.: Medieval European Coinage, I. The early Middle Ages (5th-10th centuries), Cambridge 1986, S. 329-330.
(Quelle: Auktionskatalog Knker 239, Osnabrck, Oktober 2013)

Drei Jahre nach Luthers Thesenanschlag begannen gewisse Augustiner und Kaplne Interesse fr die neue Lehre zu zeigen. Das Hauptanliegen der stdtischen Regierung war die Erhaltung von Ruhe und Ordnung. Im Jahr 1527 war schon die Mehrheit der Brger vom alten Glauben abgefallen, dennoch unterschrieb die Stadt 1530 nicht die Augsburger Konfession. Erst der Beitritt zum Schmalkaldischen Bund gab der Stadt gengend politische Strke, um die Reformation offiziell einzufhren. Whrend des Interims (1548-1551) schlug sich die Stadt auf die Seite der Kaiserlichen. Endlich, ab 1579, blieb Esslingen eine evangelische, lutherische Stadt.
Auction Name: NumisBids: SINCONA AG Auction 90

Bahrfeldt schreibt in seinem Buch ber das Mnz- und Geldwesen der Frstentmer Hohenzollern, Berlin 1890, zu den Nummern 482.5 und 482.6: Bei der ausserordentlichen Seltenheit dieser Mnzen hat man sie bisher nur an der Stelle gekannt, wo sie aufbewahrt liegen, im frstlich-frstenbergischen Mnzkabinett zu Donaueschingen. Die Akten bermitteln uns auch hier wieder erwnschte Ausknfte ber sie: Im Jahre 1840 wendete sich der Frst Karl Egon II. zu Frstenberg mit dem Ansuchen an den Frsten Karl von Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen, zu gestatten, dass fr seine Mnzensammlung mit den Hohenzollerschen Stempeln angefertigt wrden: 3 Abschlge vom 6 Kreuzerstck = 1 Dukat und 3 Abschlge vom
3 Kreuzerstck = 1/2 Dukat.
